21:48.120 --> 21:51.600
And this was a time that he was honored in Louisiana, right?

21:51.600 --> 21:52.600
Talk about this.

21:52.600 --> 21:59.600
Well, back in the 1960s during the Cuban crisis my dad, the 49th armory was called up.

21:59.600 --> 22:02.720
Headquartered out of temple, he was a battalion commander.

22:02.720 --> 22:05.360
And they were sent down to Fort Poc, Louisiana.

22:05.360 --> 22:07.600
And all the armory units of the 49th were called down there.

22:07.600 --> 22:09.760
He spent a full year down there.

22:09.760 --> 22:14.400
And so this was probably about six, seven, eight years ago.

22:14.400 --> 22:17.400
They were going on our plaque to the 49th.

22:17.400 --> 22:18.880
And he was requested to come down there.

22:18.880 --> 22:20.640
And he was, so the honoree.

22:20.640 --> 22:24.960
And it gave me an opportunity to spend time with my dad here, more of the war stories that

22:24.960 --> 22:26.320
I heard as a kid.

22:26.320 --> 22:30.760
And as you get older and you've experienced that war situation, you've been there, you

22:30.760 --> 22:34.280
can ask questions a little bit differently than if you've never seen combat.

22:34.280 --> 22:39.520
So I was able now to go in there and find out specifically what did it feel like?

22:39.520 --> 22:42.760
You know, a lot of generic terms you ask, you know, what was it like in a war?

22:42.960 --> 22:44.920
And a person will give you a generic answer.

22:44.920 --> 22:49.800
But if you ask a specific question, like when that's shrapnel buzzes by your head,

22:49.800 --> 22:53.000
or you take casualty in your hand, it's holding down a wound until the men

22:53.000 --> 22:55.600
get there, what went through your head?

22:55.600 --> 23:00.400
I was now able to discuss that with him in a sort of a soldier to soldier way.

23:00.400 --> 23:06.600
Joe, you were awarded the bronze star medal on two occasions for your action on two consecutive days.

23:06.600 --> 23:09.080
May 8th and 9th, 1970.

23:09.080 --> 23:11.200
Talking about what happened those two days.

23:11.280 --> 23:19.280
We went into Cambodia and up until then, most of our combat was small unit back in Vietnam.

23:19.280 --> 23:23.280
The kind of Cambodia was a larger unit's fight in each other.

23:23.280 --> 23:26.280
And we had landed our helicopters.

23:26.280 --> 23:28.440
I was in my opportunity with the first two to go in.

23:28.440 --> 23:32.520
And as soon as we hit the ground helicopters left, we were hit from the woodline by the NBA.

23:32.520 --> 23:35.120
They were detection of cash that was very important to them.

23:35.120 --> 23:37.880
We had to fight our way into the jungles for next two or three days.

23:37.880 --> 23:43.120
We unsuccessfully kept trying to take that cash and that particular bunker complex, which

23:43.120 --> 23:44.800
we finally did take.

23:44.800 --> 23:49.160
During that time frame, I spent a lot of time in the front giving directions, pulling

23:49.160 --> 23:54.160
wounded men back, and the Army thought that maybe I deserved a bronze star for that.

23:54.160 --> 23:57.320
I'm sure there was a lot of soldiers that did a lot more than I did that deserved a bronze

23:57.320 --> 24:00.560
star didn't get it, but somehow I got nominated for it.

24:00.560 --> 24:06.200
On the next day or two later, we were bibwacked along one of the rivers there in Cambodia,

24:06.200 --> 24:08.440
and we were hit, ready to do another mission.

24:08.440 --> 24:12.240
And the Navy came down one of the rivers there, spotted us.

24:12.240 --> 24:15.480
And they had been in the ambush several times the previous day, and they were a little bit

24:15.480 --> 24:16.480
on the touchy side.

24:16.480 --> 24:20.400
And apparently our hire command did not warn them that we were there.

24:20.400 --> 24:25.080
So they immediately opened fire with us with quad 50s, and they had an automatic 79 grenade

24:25.080 --> 24:28.360
launcher, and we started taking severe casualties.

24:28.360 --> 24:29.840
And someone had to get communication with them.

24:29.840 --> 24:32.000
We did not have their radio frequency.

24:32.000 --> 24:34.160
So someone had to get up and actually motioned them.

24:34.160 --> 24:35.640
We were Americans.

24:35.640 --> 24:39.200
And I guess I drew the black vein because I ended up being the one that did it.

24:39.200 --> 24:42.160
And apparently again, somebody thought I deserved something for that.

24:42.160 --> 24:48.480
Again, medals should have been more just than deserved elsewhere, I'm sure.

24:48.480 --> 24:52.240
We need to move along, but with about a month left in your service, you were sent to the

24:52.240 --> 24:56.720
first cavalry, but then eventually sent back to the 25th.

24:56.720 --> 25:00.600
And talk about the message that you got that the chief of staff wanted to see you and

25:00.600 --> 25:02.080
what he had to say to you.

25:02.080 --> 25:04.480
So the 25th empty vision received orders.

25:04.480 --> 25:06.640
They were going to return home.

25:06.640 --> 25:10.120
And Bobby, October, November of 1970.

25:10.120 --> 25:12.520
Because I still had a little over a month left in country.

25:12.520 --> 25:15.280
I was not able to ship home with a lot of the troops.

25:15.280 --> 25:18.520
I was sent to the first cab, figuring I still had a month and a half left, and I could

25:18.520 --> 25:19.920
be of service to them.

25:19.920 --> 25:23.760
Went to their one week school, and they realized, hey, you're a little still too sharp.

25:23.760 --> 25:25.240
You won't benefit us.

25:25.240 --> 25:28.160
And by that time I got orders to return back to the 25th infantry.

25:28.160 --> 25:31.320
Well, as soon as I hit the ground, there was a gentleman standing there, a lieutenant

25:31.320 --> 25:34.640
said that the chief of staff, full colonel, wanted to visit with me.

25:34.640 --> 25:38.840
So I entered his office, and normally a lieutenant does not want to face the chief of staff.

25:38.840 --> 25:40.920
There's something very, very wrong.

25:40.920 --> 25:42.840
This case he had my file in front of him.

25:42.840 --> 25:46.240
He indicated, well, you went to Ranger School, you went to Airborne, received a few

25:46.240 --> 25:47.240
metal.

25:47.240 --> 25:48.240
He said, you're exactly the person I'm looking for.

25:48.240 --> 25:52.280
I said, oh no, not one of these deep, short, black missions are going to send me on.

25:52.280 --> 25:56.120
And it ended up being that he needed someone to take that at the infancy, the vision colors

25:56.120 --> 25:59.240
of the 25th infantry back to Scofield Barracks in Hawaii.

25:59.240 --> 26:03.080
And they felt like that I was the white person to do that.

26:03.080 --> 26:08.600
And it was quite an honor for me to receive the orders to do this.

26:08.600 --> 26:11.840
I trained with about 30 other gentlemen.

26:11.840 --> 26:14.400
We brought all the regimental colors in.

26:14.400 --> 26:17.360
Several of these troops had been middle-owner winners.

26:17.360 --> 26:18.960
So I've got to hear their stories.

26:18.960 --> 26:21.120
They were quite the heroes.

26:21.120 --> 26:26.520
And then in the middle of December we flew into Scofield Barracks in Hawaii, met by a

26:26.520 --> 26:27.520
man.

26:27.520 --> 26:31.520
Then next couple days the colors were transferred back to the 25th there in a way.

26:31.520 --> 26:33.520
I know that was quite an honor for you.

26:33.520 --> 26:36.600
And it's something that probably, of all your memories of your Vietnam experience, it

26:36.600 --> 26:41.360
was that at the end bringing back the colors that is maybe the most meaningful to you.

26:41.360 --> 26:43.360
It is one that I'll always remember.

26:43.360 --> 26:48.720
And I just, that a lot of the soldiers that went to Vietnam did not have the great fortune

26:48.720 --> 26:51.200
I had of returning back to the United States.

26:51.200 --> 26:55.320
Most of the soldiers came back home and most of them were not met at the airports.

26:55.320 --> 26:57.760
There were no bands or anybody who would congratulate them.

26:57.760 --> 27:01.040
And yet here I was coming back with a band waiting for me.

27:01.040 --> 27:02.040
Congratulations.

27:02.040 --> 27:08.880
And so that maybe feels extremely well thought of like I, you know, my time and service

27:08.880 --> 27:09.880
